ASML, Ferrovial, SAP, ThyssenKrupp: European Equity Preview

-- B y   J e f f   K e a r n s
-- 
2011-04-13T04:00:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/asml-holding-ferrovial-sap-ag-thyssenkrupp-ag-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index fell 1.7 percent to 276.24. The
Stoxx 50 Index slipped 1.7 percent to 2,601.29. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, declined 1.4
percent to 2,932.33.  ASML Holding NV (ASML)  : Europe’s largest maker of
semiconductor-production equipment may say first-quarter net
income rose threefold to 354.4 million euros ($513.5 million),
according to the average of 21 analyst estimates compiled by
Bloomberg. ASML lost 1.4 percent to 29.42 euros.  Casino Guichard-Perrachon (CO FP): The French retailer said
first-quarter sales rose 19 percent to 7.85 billion euros. The
supermarket chain said it targets 700 million euros in asset
sales in 2011. It confirmed 2011 forecasts and said it expects
to gain market share in France this year. The shares fell 1.7
percent to 70.32 euros.  Ferrovial SA (FER)  : Spain’s second-largest builder by
market capitalization signed a 1.31 billion-euro ($1.9 billion)
four-year loan with 32 lenders, the company said in a filing to
regulators. The accord also includes a credit line of 541
million euros. The shares dropped 1.9 percent to 9 euros.  ProLogis European Properties (PEPR)  : A group of
investors led by APG Groep NV and  Goodman Group  said they plan
to make a 6 euro-per-ordinary-share takeover offer for the
warehouse fund managed by a unit of ProLogis. APG Groep and
Goodman said ProLogis, the fund’s biggest shareholder, rejected
the proposal. ProLogis European Properties rose less than 0.1
percent to 5 euros.  SAP AG (SAP)  : The world’s largest maker of business-
management software is “looking for opportunities” to fuel
growth, though it won’t make an acquisition just to increase
market share, Co-Chief Executive Officer Jim Hagemann Snabe said
in an interview with Bloomberg television in  London . The shares
declined 1.8 percent to 43.50 euros.  ThyssenKrupp AG (TKA)  :  Germany ’s biggest steelmaker is
considering the sale of units worth “several billion euros” to
reduce debt and expand its technology business,  Financial Times
Deutschland  reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares fell 3.3 percent to 29.41 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jeff Kearns in  New York  at 
 jkearns3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 